  <body>

    <h1>Ankit Bisain's Linux Commands</h1>
	<a href="index.html">go back to the original page</a>
	<table style="width:100%">
  <tr>
    <th>Name</th>
    <th>Description</th>
    <th>Usage</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Echo</td>
    <td>Typing "echo [string]" makes the computer say [string].
</td>
    <td>This can be used to display the outcome of a function (for example, the state of the rpi in the project).</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>cd</td>
    <td>Typing "cd [directory]" is used to 'enter' a directory.
</td>
    <td>This is used to access things within folders from the terminal/
</td>
  </tr>
</tr>
  <tr>
    <td>nano</td>
    <td>Typing "nano [file]" opens an editor in which you can view and change the file.
</td>
    <td>This is used to change files to write scripts and stuff.</td>
  </tr>
<tr>
    <td>clear</td>
    <td>Typing "clear" clears all commands and output from the screen.

</td>
    <td>This is typically used for aesthetic reasons
</td>
  </tr>
<tr>
    <td>man</td>
    <td>Typing "man [command]" makes a manual of how to use [command] be displayed.

</td>
    <td> This is used to find out how a command works, as well as ways it can be modified.
</td>
  </tr>
<tr>
    <td>cat</td>
    <td>Typing "cat [file]" shows the content of [file].
</td>
    <td> This is used to conveniently figure out what a file is and what is in it.

</td>
  </tr>
<tr>
    <td>ls/td>
    <td> Typing "ls" lists the current directory.

    <td> This is used to check which files exist and are currently accessible.
</td>
  </tr>

<tr>
    <td>mkdir/td>
    <td> Typing "mkdir [name]" creates a directory with the given name.
    <td> It is used to create directories to store things.
</td>
  </tr>
<tr>
    <td>rm/td>
    <td> Typing "rm [name]" removes the object with the given name.
    <td> It is used to delete redundant or useless files.
</td>
  </tr>
<tr>
    <td>scp/td>
    <td> Typing "scp [file] [location]" copies the file to the location.

    <td> It is used to move files into places so they can be accessed.

</td>
  </tr>

</table>

 </body>
</html>
